Here's an implementation of a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Use a regex to match Markdown syntax and replace with HTML equivalents
    std::regex markdownSyntax(R"([\#\*\-+])\s*(\w*)");

    std::smatch match;
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, markdownSyntax)) {
        std::string markup = match[1];
        std::string text = match[2];

        if (markup == "#") {
            html += "<h1>";
            html += text;
            html += "</h1>\n";
        } else if (markup == "*") {
            html += "<strong>";
            html += text;
            html += "</strong>";
        } else if (markup == "-") {
            html += "<em>";
            html += text;
            html += "</em>";
        } else if (markup == "+") {
            html += "<ul>";
            while (text[text.length() - 1] != '\n') {
                std::string item = text;
                text = "";
                html += "<li>";
                html += item;
                html += "</li>";
            }
            html += "</ul>";
        }

        // Erase the matched Markdown syntax from the string
        markdown.erase(match.position(), match.length());
    }

    // Check for remaining text (not part of any Markdown syntax)
    // and add as paragraphs
    if (!markdown.empty()) {
        html += "<p>";
        html += markdown;
        html += "</p>\n";
    }

    return html;
}
```

This function uses the C++11 `regex` library to convert Markdown syntax to HTML. It matches each Markdown element (e.g., `#` for heading, `*` for bold text, etc.) and replaces it with the appropriate HTML tags. Remaining text, if any, is added as paragraphs.

Remember to compile with a C++11 compatible compiler (e.g., `g++ -std=c++11 filename.cpp`). 

