You can use a discriminated union type to explicitly tell TypeScript that a particular union type will always have a specific discriminant.

Here's an example:

```typescript
type MyUnion = { kind: 'a'; value: string } | { kind: 'b'; value: number } | { kind: 'c'; value: boolean };

// This will only accept the exact object shape of MyUnion
type MySafeUnion = MyUnion;

// But this will be able to accept anything
type MyLooseUnion = any;

function processValue(value: MySafeUnion) {
  if (value.kind === 'a') {
    // TypeScript knows this is safe to cast
    const safeValue: string = value.value;
    console.log(safeValue);
  } else if (value.kind === 'b') {
    // TypeScript knows this is safe to cast
    const safeValue: number = value.value;
    console.log(safeValue);
  } else if (value.kind === 'c') {
    // TypeScript knows this is safe to cast
    const safeValue: boolean = value.value;
    console.log(safeValue);
  } else {
    console.log("Unexpected value kind");
  }
}

function main() {
  const value1: MyUnion = { kind: 'a', value: 'hello' };
  const value2: MyUnion = { kind: 'b', value: 42 };
  const value3: MyUnion = { kind: 'c', value: true };

  processValue(value1);
  processValue(value2);
  processValue(value3);

  // This will error: unexpected kind property
  const invalidValue: MyUnion = { foo: 'bar' };
  processValue(invalidValue);

  // This will also error, because the loose type accepts anything
  const looseValue: MyLooseUnion = 'foo';
  processValue(looseValue);
}

main();
```

In this example, `MyUnion` is a discriminated union where each variant has a `kind` property that discriminates between them. We have two types that accept `MyUnion`: `MySafeUnion`, which is identical to `MyUnion` and thus only accepts the exact union shape, and `MyLooseUnion`, which is `any` and thus accepts anything.

When we call `processValue`, we're safely able to cast to specific types based on the `kind` property because TypeScript knows that the only possible types are those in `MyUnion`. On the other hand, when we use `MyLooseUnion`, we can no longer use this pattern because `MyLooseUnion` could be anything.

This way, you can tell the type system "I know that in theory this value may have these multiple types, but in practice I know it will only have this one", by using a discriminated union type and only accepting values of that exact type. 

Note that this pattern assumes that you can modify your types or that the structure you're working with is under your control. If you're working with an external API or a codebase with strict compatibility requirements, you may not be able to use this pattern. 

Also, keep in mind that even with this pattern, you might not be able to prevent runtime errors that could occur if the value you're working with isn't truly one of the expected types. This pattern only provides type safety benefits, not runtime safety benefits. 

Finally, note that this pattern should not be overused. Prefer keeping your types broad when possible and only use this pattern when there's a real-world guarantee that a value can only have a specific subset of a union type. 

